System Design of a cross-sectoral energy system for heating of a city in southern Germany - System Technical Report

Introduction

In the context of the subject of energy management with AI methods, a system design for a cross-sectoral energy system for heating of a city in southern Germany is to be developed. For this project, the southern German city of Weissenburg (4901'53.5"N 1057'54.0"E) has been chosen and the data basis year is 2019.

Task

The Task is to design a system for a cross-sectoral energy system. It should at least consist of the following components:

  • Heat pump
  • PV and/or solar thermal
  • Backup or peak load system
  • Large scale thermal storage (seasonal storage)
  • Connection to the public grid (gas/electricity)

The system components should be dimensioned using oemof, and an optimized schedule needs to be developed. The share of fossil heat sources should be in all cases limited to 35%. Two optimized configurations should be explored:

  • CO2-optimized
  • Price-optimized

The following cost calculations should be made:

  • Yearly CAPEX
  • Yearly OPEX
  • Levelizeds costs of energy

Given Daten

This chapter shows all given data.

Given demands of the city

The heat demand and the electricity demand are given as normalized profiles. The peak load of the heat is 2500 kW and the peak load of the electricitiy is 850 kW. The diagramm below shows the normalized profiles:

Given cost assumptions

The following list shows the used given cost assumptions:

Cost Unit
Gas-fired CHP 750 /
Heat pump large 1500 /
Ground mounted PV 750 /
Grid fees 0,32 /
Grid fees heat pump 0,25 /
Gas 0,08 /
Balance of System 30 %

Addtionally, a cost curve of various large-scale heat storages is provided.

Researched data and assumptions

This chapter presents all the researched data and the assumptions made for the project.

Emission assumptions

The following emission of the energy carriers were used in the project:

Energy carrier Emissions in CO2 Equivalent (g/kWh)
Electricity grid supply 560
Natural gas 240

Cost Assumptions

Based on the given cost assumptions and additional research data, costs were split into CAPEX and OPEX, and the following cost assumptions were made:

Element CAPEX OPEX
Balance of system 30% of invest -
Gasfired CHP 750 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Electrical storage 450 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Heatpump large 1500 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Ground mounted PV 750 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Seasonal storage 4,2 [/h] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Heating element 80 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Wind turbine 1000 [/] + balance of system 25% of CAPEX
Grid fees - 0,32 [/]
Grid fees heatpump - 0,25 [/]
Gas - 0,08 [/]
Overall system costs 30% of all CAPEX 25% of overall system costs

The follwing additional price researches were conducted to make assumptions:

  • The costs of a 150 MWh heat storage in hannover are 4,2 /kWh.
  • In NPro, an another energy simulation tool, a document of the danish energy agency is mentioned. The economic parameters are 1000 /kW.
  • The price for a 1 MWh large size battery storage system is 438.000$.

The following additional assumptions were taken:

  • The capex of a component consists of the investment in the component and 30% of the balance of system costs.
  • The opex of a component consits of 25% of capex, it includes maintenance, operational staff wadges, licences, ... The energy costs
  • The overall system costs, which include all additional components required for the system to operate (such as the heating grid, electrical grid, etc.), constitute 30% of the total CAPEX.

Heatpump data - air temperature and COP curve

A weather station is located in Weissenburg-Emetzheim, which tracks various weather data, including air temperature. This temperature data is crucial for calculating the coefficient of performance (COP) of an air-water heat pump. The data for the base year 2019 can be downloaded from the website of the german weather service DWD. (Stationnumber: 5440). This is the temperature of the year 2019:

Based on the temperature and on a typical COP curve a temperature dependent COP is calculated. The following diagramm shows the common COP curve based on a data sheet of a heatpump:

The following diagramms shows the result of the calculation of the cop based on the temperature (The first diagram displays the COP in the year 2019, while the second one additionally includes the temperature.):

Hourly PV and wind data

The interactive tool PVGIS, which provides hourly data for PV systems based on the climate satellite-based dataset SARAH-2, is available on the website of the European Commission. A normalized PV profile for a 1 kWp system, located in Weissenburg and oriented towards the south at a 30-degree angle, was downloaded for the year 2019. The following diagramm shows the normalized PV profile:

System design

Based on the task description and the paper A modeler's guide to handle complexity in energy systems optimization the total energy system design consits of three main parts:

  • The choice which components should be used
  • The optimized size of the components
  • The optimized operation schedule

System design: choice of components

The following system design targets are used in this projects:

  • Less components to decrease the possibilities of errors and increase the simplicity of the system
  • Mostly electric heating components to include wind and photovoltaic power for a cross-sectoral system
  • High amount of renewable power to enable the energy transition
  • Expandable for power-to-gas (Hydrogen) and hydrogen based chp units

The following diagramm shows the developed system design:

System design: opimizied size of the components

Cost Calculations

  1. Calculate the LCOE (Levelized costs of energy (Heat & Electricity))
  2. Scale costs chp to electricity and heat Steps to calculate the total costs of electricity
  3. CAPEX: Calculate the total investment costs
  4. OPEX: Calculate the total operational costs
  5. Calculate the revenue of grid feed in
  6. Calculate the total costs of electricity
  7. Calculate the total electricity generation
  8. Calculate the levelized costs of electricity

Steps to calculate the levelized costs of heat:

  1. CAPEX: Calculate the total investment costs
  2. OPEX: Calculate the total operational costs
  3. Calculate the total costs of heat
  4. Calculate the total heat consumption
  5. Calculate the levelized costs of heat

Title: Technical Report on a Model of a Solar Photovoltaic (PV) Power System

Introduction This report presents the design, implementation, and testing of a scaled-down model of a solar photovoltaic (PV) power system. The model is designed to simulate a real-world PV power system and to provide a platform for studying and analyzing the performance of various components of the system.

System Design The model consists of a 1 kW solar PV array, a battery bank with a capacity of 10 kWh, and a power conditioning system. The solar PV array is mounted on a tracking system to simulate the movement of the sun. The battery bank is designed to store excess energy for use during periods of low sunlight. The power conditioning system converts the DC power generated by the PV array into AC power and regulates voltage and frequency.

System Implementation The model was implemented in a controlled laboratory environment. The solar PV array was mounted on a motorized track, and the battery bank and power conditioning system were connected to a load bank. The system was controlled and monitored using a data acquisition system.

System Testing The system was tested under various conditions to evaluate its performance. The results showed that the system was able to generate and store energy effectively. The power conditioning system was able to regulate voltage and frequency within acceptable limits.

System Analysis The data collected during the testing phase was analyzed to evaluate the performance of the system. The results showed that the system was able to generate an average of 5 kWh of energy per day. The battery bank was able to store excess energy for use during periods of low sunlight. The power conditioning system was able to regulate voltage and frequency with an efficiency of over 95%.

Conclusion The model of the solar PV power system was successful in providing a platform for studying and analyzing the performance of various components of a real-world PV power system. The system was able to generate and store energy effectively, and the power conditioning system was able to regulate voltage and frequency within acceptable limits. This model can be used for research, education, and training purposes.

Recommendations It is recommended that the model be used in conjunction with a curriculum or training program to provide a comprehensive learning experience. Additionally, it is suggested that the model be modified and updated over time to incorporate new technologies and components as they become available. Furthermore, it is recommended that the model be used in conjunction with other models or systems to provide a more holistic view of PV power systems.

Calculation of an COP Curve based on an technical report of a heatpump

The link is found here: Technical Data heatpumps [p.4]

Readout 10 Points of the diagramm and used a Spline to reengneered the diagramm: Documentation Spline

In[14]:
# Caluclate the COP based on outside temperature of the Heat Pump

def cop_calcution(temperature):
    if temperature < -10: 
        return 1.5
        # raise ValueError('Temperature is too low')
    if temperature > 35:
        return 4.7
        # raise ValueError('Temperature is too high')
    # Index begins at -10C to 35C in 5C steps
    lookup_temperatures = np.arange(-10, 36, 5)
    lookup_cop_55_degree = [ \
        1.7, # -10C
        2.0, # -5C
        2.2,  # 0 C
        2.6, # 5 C
        2.8, # 10 C
        3.0, # 15 C
        3.3, # 20 C
        3.8, # 25 C	
        4.2, # 30 C
        4.7, # 35 C
    ]

    # Create a linear interpolation function
    f = interpolate.UnivariateSpline(lookup_temperatures, lookup_cop_55_degree)
    
    # Use the function to calculate the COP at the given temperature
    return float(f(temperature))


# Define the range of values
x_values = np.linspace(-10, 35, 100)  # 100 points from -10 to 35

# Apply the function to each value
y_values = [cop_calcution(x) for x in x_values]

df = pd.DataFrame({'y': y_values}, index=x_values)
plot.timeseries(df, plot_label='COP based on temperature - common cop curve', y_axis_label='COP', x_axis_label='Temperature [C]', save_on_disk=True, width=1200, height=480)

# Apply the function to the 'temperature' column
input_data['COP'] = input_data['Temperature [C]'].apply(cop_calcution)


# This is the cop for the 500 kW heatpump of CTA AG
cop_set = 2.5 # 
# Scale the COP to the set COP
scale_factor = cop_set / input_data['COP'].mean()
input_data['COP'] = scale_factor*input_data['COP']
# Check if caluclation was correct
assert np.isclose(input_data['COP'].mean(), cop_set)

plot.timeseries(input_data[['Temperature [C]']], plot_label='Air temperature of german weather station DWD 5440', y_axis_label='Temperature [C]', save_on_disk=True)
plot.timeseries(input_data[['COP']], plot_label='COP based on temperature', y_axis_label='COP', save_on_disk=True, width=1200, height=480)
plot.timeseries(input_data[['COP', 'Temperature [C]']], plot_label='COP based on temperature 2019', y_axis_label='COP', y2_axis_label='Temperature [C]',y2_axis_columns=['Temperature [C]'],save_on_disk=True, width=1200, height=480)

if investmentoptimization of renewables is active the optimzizer optimizes to the maximum of the renewabl, because you earn money with renewables

Personnel and maintenance costs: Around 2% to 5% of the CAPEX per year Insurance costs: Around 0.1% to 0.5% of the CAPEX per year Taxes and fees: Around 1% to 5% of the CAPEX per year Repair and replacement part costs: Around 0.5% to 2% of the CAPEX per year Financing costs: Around 3% to 10% of the CAPEX per year Cleaning and maintenance costs: Around 1% to 3% of the CAPEX per year Monitoring and control costs: Around 0.5% to 2% of the CAPEX per year Legal and compliance costs: Around 1% to 5% of the CAPEX per year Other costs: Varies depending on the project and location.

Total OPEX costs range from around 10% to 25% of the CAPEX per year

# TODO parameter ergnzen
import dataclasses

# Switch between invest optimization to calculate the optimal size of the components and fixed size of the components
invest_optimization = True


# Demand parameters
thermal_peak_load = 2500 # kW
electric_peak_load = 850 # kW

## Sytem Boundaries Power
pv_power_max_bound = 3000 # kWp 
pv_power_min_bound = 0 # kWp
wind_power_max_bound = 3000 # kW
wind_power_min_bound = 0 # kW

# for invest optimization
heatpump_power_max_bound = 1000 # kW
heatpump_power_min_bound = 0 # kW

heating_element_power_max_bound = 20000 # kW electrical
heating_element_power_min_bound = 0 # kW electrical

chp_power_max_bound = 500 # kW eletrical
chp_power_min_bound = 0 # kW eletrical

thermal_storage_max_bound = 1000000 # kWh
thermal_storage_min_bound = 10000 # kWh # 20 MWh minimum invest for this price 

## for fixed size and planing schedule
heatpump_minimum_power = 0.3 # normed to nominal value of heatpump #  if this value is higher than 0, the calucation takes very long!
heatpump_maximum_power = 1.0 # normed to nominal value of heatpump

gradient_limit_heatpump = 0.5 # normed to nominal value of heatpump

## System Boundaries down and up times
heatpump_minimum_downtime = 8 # h
heatpump_minimum_uptime = 7 # h
heatpump_maximum_startups = 365 # in one year


# OPEX: variable costs parameters energy costs
grid_feed_in_pv =  0.10     #0.058 # /kWh # 0.10 /kWh # 0.058 /kWh
grid_feed_in_conventional = 0.05 # /kWh
grid_fees = 0.32 # /kWh 
grid_fees_heatpump = 0.25 # /kWh 
gas_costs = 0.08 # /kWh

opex_as_percentage_of_capex  = 0.25 # % of capex # costs of maintenance, insurance, etc.

# CAPEX: investment costs parameters
balance_of_system = 1.3 # %/invest

# for short time simulation periods
time_scaler = input_data.shape[0]/8760
years_at_interest = 20 # years
interest_rate = 0.05 # %

capex_heating_element = 80*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW
capex_gas_fired_chp = 750*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW electrical
capex_heatpump_large = 1500*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW electrical
capex_ground_mounted_pv = 750*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kWp
capex_wind_power = 1000*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW

capex_biomass_boiler = 500*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW thermal
capex_gas_boiler = 150*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kW

capex_thermal_storage = 4.2*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kWh thermal
capex_electrical_storage = 450*balance_of_system*time_scaler # /kWh electrical


# Capex 1500 /kW , costs n = 15 years at 5% interest rate in one year
invest_heating_element = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_heating_element, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate) 
invest_gas_fired_chp = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_gas_fired_chp, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate) 
invest_heatpump_large = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_heatpump_large, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)
invest_ground_mounted_pv = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_ground_mounted_pv, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)
invest_wind_power = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_wind_power, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)

invest_biomass_boiler = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_biomass_boiler, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)
invest_gas_boiler = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_gas_boiler, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)

invest_thermal_storage = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_thermal_storage, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)
invest_electrical_storage = time_scaler*economics.annuity(capex=capex_electrical_storage, n=years_at_interest, wacc=interest_rate)


## Fixed Nominal Parameters
nominal_power_chp = 200 # kW electrical
nominal_power_heatpump = 500 # kW electrical
nominal_power_heating_element = 3000 # kW electrical

nominal_power_pv = 3000 # kWp
nominal_power_wind = 3000 # kW

# Storage parameters
# electrical storage
charge_power = 2000 # Charging power battery kW
discharge_power = 2000 # Discharging power in kW
batt_store_cap = 4000 # Battery capacity in kWh
batt_init_level = 0.5 # Initial state of charge of battery

# thermal storage
thermal_storage_cap = 150000 # Therm capacity in kWh

# Efficiency parameters
conversion_factor_heating_element = 1
conversion_factor_chp_eletric = 0.35
conversion_factor_chp_thermal = 0.55


# Emmission factors
emission_factor_gas = 0.240 # kg/kWh
emission_factor_grid = 0.560 # kg/kWh

co2_limit = 10000000 # kg CO2 # 241.05 t CO2'
co2_costs = 0#1000 # if this > 0 then the co2 limit is optimized, the costs are not correct

In[28]:
#create an empty energy schedule
energy_schedule = pd.DataFrame()
# add index to the energy schedule 
energy_schedule.index = input_data.index

# 1. # Define energy system and set time basis
energy_system = solph.EnergySystem(timeindex=energy_schedule.index, infer_last_interval=True)

# 2. Definition Buses
## Electric busses
# renewable bus
electric_bus_renewables = solph.buses.Bus(label='electric_bus_renewables')
# general electric bus
electric_bus_general = solph.buses.Bus(label='electric_bus_general')
# conventional electric bus
electric_bus_conventional = solph.buses.Bus(label='electric_bus_conventional')
# electric bus heatpump
electric_bus_heatpump = solph.buses.Bus(label='electric_bus_heatpump')

# Heating bus
thermal_bus = solph.buses.Bus(label='thermal_bus')
# Gas bus
gas_bus = solph.buses.Bus(label='gas_bus')


# Define sources, sinks, transformers, storages 
# 3. Define sources 

# Gas source
source_gas_grid = solph.components.Source(label='gas_grid',
                    outputs={gas_bus: solph.Flow(variable_costs=gas_costs+(emission_factor_gas*co2_costs),
                                                 custom_attributes={"emission_factor": emission_factor_gas})})   

# Public grid
source_public_grid = solph.components.Source(label='public_grid',
                    outputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(variable_costs=grid_fees+(emission_factor_grid*co2_costs), 
                                                              custom_attributes={"emission_factor": emission_factor_grid})})   

source_public_grid_heatpump = solph.components.Source(label='public_grid_heatpump',
                    outputs={electric_bus_heatpump: solph.Flow(variable_costs=grid_fees_heatpump+(emission_factor_grid*co2_costs), 
                                                               custom_attributes={"emission_factor": emission_factor_grid})})  

# pv generation
if invest_optimization:
    electric_flow_pv = solph.Flow(fix=(input_data['PV [norm kWp]']),
                                                    investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_ground_mounted_pv, minimum=pv_power_min_bound, maximum=pv_power_max_bound))
                                                    #nominal_value=nominal_power_pv)})  
else:
    electric_flow_pv = solph.Flow(fix=(input_data['PV [norm kWp]']), nominal_value=nominal_power_pv)
    
source_pv = solph.components.Source(label='pv_generation',
                    outputs={electric_bus_renewables: electric_flow_pv}) 

# wind generation
if invest_optimization:
    eletric_flow_wind = solph.Flow(fix=(input_data['Wind [norm kW]']),
                                                    investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_wind_power, minimum=wind_power_min_bound, maximum=wind_power_max_bound))
else:
    eletric_flow_wind = solph.Flow(fix=(input_data['Wind [norm kW]']), nominal_value=nominal_power_wind)
    
source_wind = solph.components.Source(label='wind_generation',
                    outputs={electric_bus_renewables: eletric_flow_wind})


# 4. Define transfomers
# heatpump
if invest_optimization:
    # nonconvex optimization takes too long calculation time
    electric_flow_heatpump = solph.Flow(
                                        nonconvex=solph.NonConvex(
                                            minimum_uptime=heatpump_minimum_uptime,
                                            minimum_downtime=heatpump_minimum_downtime,
                                            maximum_startups=heatpump_maximum_startups,
                                            initial_status=0
                                        ),
                                        # min=heatpump_minimum_power,
                                        # max=heatpump_maximum_power,
                                        # positive_gradient_limit=gradient_limit_heatpump,
                                        # negative_gradient_limit=-gradient_limit_heatpump,
                                        investment=solph.Investment(
                                            ep_costs=invest_heatpump_large,
                                            minimum=heatpump_power_min_bound,
                                            maximum=heatpump_power_max_bound
                                        )
                                        )
else:
    electric_flow_heatpump = solph.Flow(#min=heatpump_minimum_power, 
                                       #max=heatpump_maximum_power,
                                       positive_gradient_limit=gradient_limit_heatpump,
                                       negative_gradient_limit=gradient_limit_heatpump,
                                       nominal_value=nominal_power_heatpump,
                                       nonconvex=solph.NonConvex(minimum_uptime=heatpump_minimum_uptime,
                                                                 minimum_downtime=heatpump_minimum_downtime,
                                                                 maximum_startups=heatpump_maximum_startups,
                                                                 initial_status=0))

heatpump = solph.components.Converter(label='heatpump',
                                    inputs={electric_bus_heatpump: electric_flow_heatpump},
                                    outputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow()},
                                    conversion_factors={thermal_bus: input_data['COP']})


# chp
if invest_optimization:
    electric_flow_chp = solph.Flow(investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_gas_fired_chp,
                                                              minimum=chp_power_min_bound,
                                                              maximum=chp_power_max_bound))
else:
    electric_flow_chp = solph.Flow(nominal_value=nominal_power_chp)

chp = solph.components.Converter(label='chp',
                                    inputs={gas_bus: solph.Flow()},
                                    outputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(), 
                                             electric_bus_conventional: electric_flow_chp},
                                    conversion_factors={thermal_bus: conversion_factor_chp_thermal,
                                                        electric_bus_conventional:conversion_factor_chp_eletric})


# heating element
if invest_optimization:
    eletric_flow_heating_element = solph.Flow(investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_heating_element,
                                                              minimum=heating_element_power_min_bound,
                                                              maximum=heating_element_power_max_bound))
else:
    eletric_flow_heating_element = solph.Flow(nominal_value=nominal_power_heating_element)

heating_element = solph.components.Converter(label='heating_element',
                                    inputs={electric_bus_heatpump: eletric_flow_heating_element},
                                    outputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow()},
                                    conversion_factors={thermal_bus: conversion_factor_heating_element})


## 1:1 connections
# self consumption
renewable_to_electric = solph.components.Converter(label='renewable_to_electric',
                                        inputs={electric_bus_renewables: solph.Flow()},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow()},
                                        conversion_factors={electric_bus_general: 1.0})

conventional_to_electric = solph.components.Converter(label='conventional_to_electric',
                                        inputs={electric_bus_conventional: solph.Flow()},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow()},
                                        conversion_factors={electric_bus_general: 1.0})

renewable_to_heatpump = solph.components.Converter(label='renewable_to_heatpump',
                                        inputs={electric_bus_renewables: solph.Flow()},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_heatpump: solph.Flow()},
                                        conversion_factors={electric_bus_general: 1.0})

conventional_to_heatpump = solph.components.Converter(label='conventional_to_heatpump',
                                        inputs={electric_bus_conventional: solph.Flow()},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_heatpump: solph.Flow()},
                                        conversion_factors={electric_bus_general: 1.0})



# 5. Define consumers
heat_demand = solph.components.Sink(label='heat_demand',
                                                inputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(fix=input_data['Heat Demand [norm kW]'],
                                                                                nominal_value=thermal_peak_load)})

electrical_demand = solph.components.Sink(label='electrical_demand',
                                                inputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(fix=input_data['Electricity  Demand [norm kW]'],
                                                                                nominal_value=electric_peak_load)})

# Feed in
feed_in_renewables = solph.components.Sink(label='grid_feed_in_renewables',
                inputs={electric_bus_renewables: solph.Flow(variable_costs=-grid_feed_in_pv)})

feed_in_conventional = solph.components.Sink(label='grid_feed_in_conventional',
                inputs={electric_bus_conventional: solph.Flow(variable_costs=-grid_feed_in_conventional)})


# 6. Define storages  
if invest_optimization:
    battery_storage = solph.components.GenericStorage(label='battery_storage',
                                        investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_electrical_storage),
                                        inputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(nominal_value=charge_power)},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(nominal_value=discharge_power)},
                                        initial_storage_level=0.5,
                                        inflow_conversion_factor=0.9, 
                                        outflow_conversion_factor=0.9, 
                                        balanced=True)
else:
    battery_storage = solph.components.GenericStorage(label='battery_storage',
                                        nominal_storage_capacity=batt_store_cap,
                                        inputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(nominal_value=charge_power)},
                                        outputs={electric_bus_general: solph.Flow(nominal_value=discharge_power)},
                                        initial_storage_level=0.5,
                                        inflow_conversion_factor=0.9, 
                                        outflow_conversion_factor=0.9, 
                                        balanced=True)

if invest_optimization:
    thermal_storage = solph.components.GenericStorage(label='thermal_storage',
                                        investment=solph.Investment(ep_costs=invest_thermal_storage),
                                        inputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(nominal_value=thermal_peak_load)},
                                        outputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(nominal_value=thermal_peak_load)},
                                        initial_storage_level=0.5,
                                        inflow_conversion_factor=0.95, 
                                        outflow_conversion_factor=0.95, 
                                        balanced=True, )
else:
    thermal_storage = solph.components.GenericStorage(label='thermal_storage',
                                        nominal_storage_capacity=thermal_storage_cap,
                                        inputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(nominal_value=thermal_peak_load)},
                                        outputs={thermal_bus: solph.Flow(nominal_value=thermal_peak_load)},
                                        initial_storage_level=0.5,
                                        inflow_conversion_factor=0.95, 
                                        outflow_conversion_factor=0.95, 
                                        balanced=True, )



# Add buses to energy system ,source_pv, sink_electric_consumer4
## electric buses
energy_system.add(electric_bus_general, electric_bus_renewables, electric_bus_conventional, electric_bus_heatpump)
## thermal buses and gas bus
energy_system.add(thermal_bus, gas_bus)

# Add Sources to energy system
energy_system.add(source_public_grid, source_public_grid_heatpump, source_pv, source_wind, source_gas_grid)

# Add Storage to energy system
energy_system.add(thermal_storage, battery_storage)

# Add Sinks to energy system
energy_system.add(heat_demand, electrical_demand, feed_in_renewables, feed_in_conventional) 

# Add Transformer to energy system
# 1:1
energy_system.add(renewable_to_electric, conventional_to_electric, renewable_to_heatpump, conventional_to_heatpump)
# devices
energy_system.add(heating_element, heatpump, chp)

# Build energy system model
oemof_model = solph.Model(energy_system)


constraints.emission_limit(oemof_model, limit=co2_limit)

# print out the emission constraint
#oemof_model.integral_limit_emission_factor_constraint.pprint()
#oemof_model.integral_limit_emission_factor.pprint()



# Solve energy system problem
# if 'tee':True the solver will be verbose
oemof_model.solve(solver='gurobi',solve_kwargs={'tee': True}) # Ausgabe solver 'tee': True


# Read results
results = solph.processing.results(oemof_model)

all_results = pd.DataFrame()
# Compile results 
all_results = pd.concat([solph.views.node(results,'electric_bus_general')['sequences'],
                         solph.views.node(results,'electric_bus_conventional')['sequences'],
                            solph.views.node(results,'electric_bus_heatpump')['sequences'],
                            solph.views.node(results, 'electric_bus_renewables')['sequences'],
                    solph.views.node(results,'thermal_bus')['sequences'],
                    solph.views.node(results,'gas_bus')['sequences']],axis=1)



# Read meta results
meta_results = solph.processing.meta_results(oemof_model)

# read optimum of objective function from meta results  
cost_opt = meta_results['objective']

all_results.dropna(inplace=True)

all_results.columns = [str(i[1][0])+':'+str(i[0]).replace('(','').replace(')','').replace('\'', '').replace(',',' \u2192 ') for i in all_results.columns]

energy_schedule = all_results

#res_bel['battery_level'] = batt_init_level*batt_store_cap + res_bel['battery_level']

# First Try to calculate the LCOH

electrical_energy_consumption = input_data['Electricity  Demand [norm kW]'].sum()*electric_peak_load+total_feed_in
heat_energy_consumption = input_data['Heat Demand [norm kW]'].sum()*thermal_peak_load

kwh_to_gwh = 1/1000000

display('Electrical energy consumption: {:0.2f} GWh'.format(electrical_energy_consumption*kwh_to_gwh))
display('Heat energy consumption: {:0.2f} GWh'.format(heat_energy_consumption*kwh_to_gwh))


system_costs = optimal_electric_power_chp*invest_gas_fired_chp + \
                optimal_electric_power_heatpump*invest_heatpump_large + \
                optimal_electric_power_heating_element*invest_heating_element + \
                nominal_power_pv*invest_ground_mounted_pv + \
                nominal_power_wind*invest_wind_power + \
                batt_store_cap*invest_electrical_storage + \
                thermal_storage_cap*invest_thermal_storage
                
display(system_costs*years_at_interest)

total_costs = oemof_model.objective() + system_costs # costs in  for one simulation period
display('Total costs: {:0.2f} '.format(total_costs))
total_consumption = electrical_energy_consumption + heat_energy_consumption
display('Total consumption: {:0.2f} kWh'.format(total_consumption))
cost_of_energy = total_costs / total_consumption

display('Cost of energy: {:0.2f} /kWh'.format(cost_of_energy))

# Selling electricity to households
scaling_cost_factor_heat = 0.3 # 50% of the costs are for heating
scaling_cost_factor_electrical = 1-scaling_cost_factor_heat # 50% of the costs are for electricity
total_costs_heat = total_costs*scaling_cost_factor_heat
total_costs_eletrical = total_costs*scaling_cost_factor_electrical

display(total_costs_heat)
display(total_costs_eletrical)

lcoe = total_costs_eletrical / electrical_energy_consumption
lcoh = total_costs_heat / heat_energy_consumption

display(lcoe)
display(lcoh)

In[35]:
# 2. try to calculate the LCOE (Levelized costs of energy (Heat & Electricity))
# Scaler costs chp to electricity and heat 1 = 100% of costs to electricity, 0 = 100% of costs to heat
scaler_costs_chp_electricity = 0.6
scaler_costs_chp_heat = 1-scaler_costs_chp_electricity

energy_renewable_generation = energy_schedule[columns_flows_renewable_generation].sum(axis=0).sum()
energy_renewable_flow_to_heatpump = energy_schedule[column_renewable_flow_to_heatpump].sum(axis=0).sum()
scaler_costs_renewables_heat = energy_renewable_flow_to_heatpump/energy_renewable_generation           # 0 = 100% of costs to electricity, 1 = 100% of costs to heat
scaler_costs_renewables_electricity = 1-scaler_costs_renewables_heat
display(scaler_costs_renewables_heat)

# Part 1: Calculate the levelized costs of electricity
# Step 1: Calculate the total costs of electricity
# Step 1a: CAPEX: Calculate the total investment costs 
capex_electricity = scaler_costs_renewables_electricity*invest_wind_power*optimal_electric_power_wind+\
                    scaler_costs_renewables_electricity*invest_ground_mounted_pv*optimal_electric_power_pv+\
                    scaler_costs_chp_electricity*invest_gas_fired_chp*optimal_electric_power_chp+\
                    invest_electrical_storage*optimal_electric_storage_cap
capex_electricity = capex_electricity*balance_of_system

# Step 1b: OPEX: Calculate the total operational costs
imported_gas_costs = scaler_costs_chp_electricity*float(energy_schedule[column_gas_import].sum())*gas_costs
imported_electricity_costs = float(energy_schedule[column_elecricity_import].sum())*grid_fees
opex_electricity = capex_electricity*opex_as_percentage_of_capex+imported_gas_costs+imported_electricity_costs

# Step 1c: Calculate the revenue of grid feed in
revenue_grid_feed_in_renewable = float(energy_schedule[columns_feed_in_renewable].sum())*grid_feed_in_pv
revenue_grid_feed_in_conventional = float(energy_schedule[columns_feed_in_conventional].sum())*grid_feed_in_conventional
revenue_grid_feed_in = revenue_grid_feed_in_renewable+revenue_grid_feed_in_conventional

# Step 1d: Calculate the total costs of electricity
total_costs_electricity = capex_electricity + opex_electricity #- revenue_grid_feed_in



# Step 2: Calculate the total electricity generation
total_eletricity_generated = input_data['Electricity  Demand [norm kW]'].sum()*electric_peak_load+total_feed_in

# Step 3: Calculate the levelized costs of electricity
levelized_costs_of_electricity = total_costs_electricity / (total_eletricity_generated * time_scaler)
display(f'capex electricity: {capex_electricity:0.2f} ')
display(f'opex electricity: {opex_electricity:0.2f} ')
display(f'total electricity generated: {total_eletricity_generated:0.2f} kWh')
display(f'levelized costs of electricity: {levelized_costs_of_electricity:0.4f} /kWh')


# Part 2: Calculate the levelized costs of heat
# Step 1: Calculate the total costs of heat
# Step 1a: CAPEX: Calculate the total investment costs
capex_heat = scaler_costs_renewables_heat*invest_wind_power*optimal_electric_power_wind+\
             scaler_costs_renewables_heat*invest_ground_mounted_pv*optimal_electric_power_pv+\
             invest_heatpump_large*optimal_electric_power_heatpump+\
             invest_gas_fired_chp*optimal_electric_power_chp*scaler_costs_chp_heat+\
             invest_heating_element*optimal_electric_power_heating_element+\
             invest_thermal_storage*optimal_thermal_storage_cap
capex_heat = capex_heat*balance_of_system

# Step 1b: OPEX: Calculate the total operational costs
imported_gas_costs = scaler_costs_chp_heat*float(energy_schedule[column_gas_import].sum())*gas_costs
imported_electricity_costs = float(energy_schedule[column_elecricity_import_heatpump].sum())*grid_fees_heatpump
opex_electricity = capex_heat*opex_as_percentage_of_capex+imported_gas_costs+imported_electricity_costs

# Step 1c: Calculate the total costs of heat
total_costs_heat = capex_heat + opex_electricity

# Step 2: Calculate the total heat consumption
total_consumption_heat = input_data['Heat Demand [norm kW]'].sum()*thermal_peak_load

# Step 3: Calculate the levelized costs of heat
levelized_costs_of_heat = total_costs_heat / (total_consumption_heat * time_scaler)

display(f'capex heat: {capex_heat:0.2f} ')
display(f'opex heat: {opex_electricity:0.2f} ')
display(f'total heat consumption: {total_consumption_heat:0.2f} kWh')
display(f'levelized costs of heat: {levelized_costs_of_heat:0.4f} /kWh')

import plotly.graph_objects as go
import plotly.io as pio


keywords = ['f:']
linked_columns = [col for col in energy_schedule.columns if all(keyword in col for keyword in keywords)]

set_of_all_words = set()
for i in linked_columns:
  replaced = i.replace('f:','').replace(' ','')
  words = replaced.split('\u2192')
  set_of_all_words.add(words[0])
  set_of_all_words.add(words[1])

# list of all words
words_list = list(set_of_all_words)
# create dictionary 
word_to_number = {word: index for index, word in enumerate(words_list)}

# words to numbers
sources = []
targets = []
for i in linked_columns:
  replaced = i.replace('f:','').replace(' ','')
  words = replaced.split('\u2192')
  sources.append(word_to_number[words[0]])
  targets.append(word_to_number[words[1]])


node_labels = list(word_to_number.keys())

# sumarize the flows
summarized_flows = []
for i in linked_columns:
  summarized_flows.append(energy_schedule[i].sum())


# Sankey-Diagramm erstellen
fig = go.Figure(data=[go.Sankey(
    node = dict(
      label = node_labels,
    ),
    link = dict(
      source = sources, # Indices der Quellknoten
      target = targets, # Indices der Zielknoten
      value = summarized_flows,   # Gre der Verbindungen
      label = linked_columns, # Beschriftungen der Links
      color = 'rgba(211, 211, 211, 0.5)' 
  ))])

# Diagramm anzeigen
#fig = go.Figure()
fig.show()

# Diagramm als SVG-Datei speichern
pio.write_image(fig, '1_plot/sankey_diagramm.svg', format='svg', width=1200, height=480)
